● Good — now I can see the situation clearly. The header + nav block is duplicated verbatim across every article
  page (and index.html), with only the path depth changing (../../../ vs root).

  Plain JS fetch-and-inject is the right call for now. Here's my thinking:

  Why it fits well here:
  - Zero build tooling — stays consistent with the "pure HTML, open directly in browser" ethos
  - A single fetch('header.html').then(inject) call per page, ~10 lines, is genuinely simple
  - When you add or change the header/nav (which will happen as the nav evolves), you edit one file
  - Works fine on Nginx static serving — no server-side rendering needed
  - The ../../../ depth issue becomes a non-problem if you use an absolute path (/header.html) once the site is on
  the VM

  The one gotcha to plan for:
  - It won't render from file:// URLs (CORS blocks fetch for local files). Right now you likely open the site
  directly in a browser — you'd need a local dev server (python -m http.server) once you make this change. Worth
  knowing upfront.

  React/Next.js later: Good instinct to defer it. The only thing that would genuinely pull this toward React is if
  the index page grows into something dynamic (user accounts, comments, server-side personalisation). A daily
  static diary doesn't need that. If you go that route, fetch-and-inject is easy to rip out — it's not a trap.

  Verdict: Go with fetch-and-inject. It's the minimum viable fix with no downside at the current scale.

  Shall I implement it? I'd suggest extracting header.html + nav.html (or a combined header-nav.html) and adding a
  small components.js loader.



